            "answer_text": "I agree with Dave Setchell \u2019s response for the most part. I will add that Freddie was already having multiple seizures in early 1985 and had an EXTREME case of oral thrush in June of 1985 and was apparently unresolved in July \u201985 as his doctor advised that Freddie not participate in Live Aid. I'm sure doctors had told him many times to let his voice rest due to chronic issues with vocal polyps\u2026however that the doctor was specific about \u201dLive Aid\u201d it leads me to believe he was having uniquely serious problems with his throat. Especially since he already had two months vocal rest as the last concert date before the July 13 Live Aid show\u2026 WAS May 15. If it was just vocal nodules, he would be easily been recovered enough in 8 weeks. That the doctor was STILL advising he not do the show, there was something more serious going on, IMO. Friends say that Freddie \u201dsuddenly\u201d disappeared from Munich in mid to late 1985. Mary Austin said Freddie \u201dknew\u201d during the \u201dMagic Tour\u201d which started June 1986. So, if I had to make a bet, whether he was officially \u201ddiagnosed\u201d in 1985, or if he just \u201dknew\u201d something was seriously wrong\u2026 I think he had at least SOME idea he was sick during \u201dWho Wants to Live Forever\u201d. ",
